Exercise 1

I am curious is the amount of grogg (i.e.Â a pirate drink) a pirate can drink is predicted by how tall they are.

Visualizing Grogg x Height

Below I have created a basic scatterplot visualization. Your task is to improve the graph by: Cleaning up all of the labels, adding a title, adding a âlmâ line, and add a theme. See https://ggplot2-book.org/polishing.html for a list of included themes. Finally, interpret what you see.

ggplot(pirates, aes(x = height, y = grogg)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  labs(title = "Height x Grogg", x = "Height", y = "Grogg") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_minimal()

Slight negative relationship between height and grogg such as height increases, gross decreases (and vice versa)

Simple Regression Grogg x Height

Exercise 4: Multiple Regression with Main Effects

Below I have created the model object mod.main where I ran a multiple regression predicting life expectancy from Income and Frost (mean number of days with minimum temperature below freezing). Your task is to interpret the model output. Specifically, interpret the: Intercept, Income row, Frost row, and relevant p values.

mod.main <- lm(`Life Exp` ~ Income + Frost, states)

Exercise 5: Multiple Regression with an Interaction Effect

Below I have created the model object mod.int where I ran a multiple regression predicting life expectancy from Income and Frost (mean number of days with minimum temperature below freezing). In addition, I am testing the interaction of Income and Frost on Life Expectancy, Your task is to interpret the model output. Specifically, interpret the: Intercept, Income row, Frost row, and relevant p values. The Income:Frost row is the row that tests the interaction. For this row, you only have to interpret the p value and not the estimate. You will interpret the interaction in the next exercise (#6).

mod.int <- lm(`Life Exp` ~ Income * Frost, states)
summary(mod.int)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = `Life Exp` ~ Income * Frost, data = states)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.7176 -0.8212 -0.2645  0.9328  1.9908 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   5.826e+01  2.491e+00  23.394  < 2e-16 ***
## Income        2.731e-03  5.646e-04   4.837 1.51e-05 ***
## Frost         9.850e-02  2.269e-02   4.341 7.70e-05 ***
## Income:Frost -2.081e-05  5.005e-06  -4.157 0.000139 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.088 on 46 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3835, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3433 
## F-statistic: 9.539 on 3 and 46 DF,  p-value: 5.18e-05

Intercept: The predicted life expectancy for 0 income and 0 frost is 58.26. Income: there is a significant main effect of income such that for every one unit increase in income, life expectancy increases by .0027. Frost: there is a significant main effect of frost such that for every one unit increase in frost, life expectancy is predicted to increase by .0985. Income:Frost: There is a significant interaction effect of income and frost on life expectancy.

Exercise 6: Visualizing the Interaction

The visualization below plots the interaction of Income*Frost on Life Expectancy. You can interpret +1 SD as âHigh Frostâ and -1 SD as âLow Frostâ

Below the graph write your interpretation of how Income and Frost interact to predict Life Expectancy.

library(interactions)
interact_plot(mod.int, pred = Income, modx = Frost, modx.values = "plus-minus")

There is a significant interaction effect of income and frost on life expectancy. When income is low, high frost leads to higher life expectancy. However, when income is high, low frost leads to higher life expectancy.

Exercise 7: Model Comparison

We have run two models: mod.main and mod.int

Your task is to decide which model is the most optimal. Which of the below objects would you use to compare the models? Then, do so. Which model is most optimal and why?

objects(summary(mod.main))
##  [1] "adj.r.squared" "aliased"       "call"          "coefficients" 
##  [5] "cov.unscaled"  "df"            "fstatistic"    "r.squared"    
##  [9] "residuals"     "sigma"         "terms"
objects(summary(mod.int))
##  [1] "adj.r.squared" "aliased"       "call"          "coefficients" 
##  [5] "cov.unscaled"  "df"            "fstatistic"    "r.squared"    
##  [9] "residuals"     "sigma"         "terms"
summary(mod.main)$adj.r.squared # 0.12
## [1] 0.1157843
summary(mod.int)$adj.r.squared  #0.34
## [1] 0.3433067

Adjusted r squared is used to compare models. The interaction model explains more variance (34%) than the main effect model (12%) and therefore the interaction model is most optimal.

Logistic Regression

With logistic regression, the change is that our outcome variable (DV) is now binary (0,1). We will walk through an example using simulated data from UCLAâs stats department.

A researcher is interested in how variables, such as GRE (Graduate Record Exam scores), GPA (grade point average) and prestige of the undergraduate institution, effect admission into graduate school. The response variable, admit/donât admit, is a binary variable.

mydata <- read.csv("https://stats.idre.ucla.edu/stat/data/binary.csv")
glimpse(mydata)
## Rows: 400
## Columns: 4
## $ admit <int> 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 1â¦
## $ gre   <int> 380, 660, 800, 640, 520, 760, 560, 400, 540, 700, 800, 440, 760,â¦
## $ gpa   <dbl> 3.61, 3.67, 4.00, 3.19, 2.93, 3.00, 2.98, 3.08, 3.39, 3.92, 4.00â¦
## $ rank  <int> 3, 3, 1, 4, 4, 2, 1, 2, 3, 2, 4, 1, 1, 2, 1, 3, 4, 3, 2, 1, 3, 2â¦

Below I create a logistic regression model object called mod.log

This predicts admission from gpa.

mod.log <- glm(admit ~ gpa, data = mydata, family = "binomial")
summary(mod.log)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = admit ~ gpa, family = "binomial", data = mydata)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.1131  -0.8874  -0.7566   1.3305   1.9824  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -4.3576     1.0353  -4.209 2.57e-05 ***
## gpa           1.0511     0.2989   3.517 0.000437 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 499.98  on 399  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 486.97  on 398  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 490.97
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

The logistic regression coefficients give the change in the log odds of the outcome for a one unit increase in the predictor variable.

For a one unit increase in gpa, the log odds of being admitted to graduate school (versus non-admission) increases by 1.05. This is a significant main effect.

Exercise 8: Make 4 predictions

Now, your job is to make predictions for 4 different gpa values of your choice and interpret how they impact the probability of admission. I have put in the placeholder values of â1, 2, 3, 4â

Your job is to replace these with 4 different gpa values and to then interpret how they impact admission probability.

test.values <- data.frame(gpa = c(1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 3.9))
mod.log %>% predict(test.values, type = "response") %>%
  round(2)
##    1    2    3    4 
## 0.06 0.15 0.34 0.44

Admission probability increases as gpa increases

Below I plot the variable PHYS, which is the physical ability of the judges. As you can see, we have a skew.

ggplot(judges, aes(PHYS)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 7) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Physical Ability", y = "Frequency", title = "Judge's Physical Activity is Left Skewed")

By applying a log transformation I am able to help normalize the variable.

ggplot(judges, aes(log(PHYS))) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 6) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "log(Physical Ability)", y = "Frequency", title = "Log helps to Normalize Skew")

Below I create model object mod.log3 where I predict the log of Physical ability from rated Demeanor and Diligence. Since we logged the DV, it is now a bit trickier to interpret the estimates.

mod.log3 <- lm(log(PHYS) ~ DMNR + DILG, judges)
summary(mod.log3)

mod.log3 %>%

For each additional unit that DILG increases, the PHYS is expected to be higher, on average, by a factor of 1.07.
